<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="218" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[130,646,163,1529]" box="[130,398,293,319]" pageId="13" pageNumber="218">
<emphasis box="[130,398,293,319]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="218">Descriptive characters</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[130,646,163,1529]" pageId="13" pageNumber="218">
A very large 
<taxonomicName box="[354,434,327,352]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="218" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[354,434,327,352]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="218">Myotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with a forearm length of 65.1–68.0 mm based on 5 speci- mens from 
<collectingCountry box="[265,379,395,421]" name="Myanmar" pageId="13" pageNumber="218">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
(
<tableCitation box="[395,486,395,421]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="7.[130,143,167,188]" captionTargetId="graphics@7.[127,1200,376,1322]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 4. External and bacular measurements (in mm) and body mass (in g) of 21 species of Vespertilionidae recorded from Myanmar, including the lengths of head and body (HB), tail (TAIL), foot (HF), tibia (TIBIA), forearm (FA), fifth, fourth, third metacarpal (5MET, 4MET and 3MET), ear (E), and baculum (BAC LGT). Sample sizes for males and females differing from those reported under n are given in parentheses after the measurement. Mean and SD are included when sample size is 3 or more. Data in italics are based on specimens collected outside Myanmar. Species listed in order of genera, and taxonomic groups and subgroups based on Corbet and Hill (1992) and Bates and Harrison (1997)" pageId="13" pageNumber="218">Table 4</tableCitation>
) (FA = 65.0– 
<quantity box="[130,235,429,455]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.89" pageId="13" pageNumber="218" unit="mm" value="68.9">68.9 mm</quantity>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="HENDRICHSEN, D. K. &amp; P. J. J. BATES &amp; B. D. HAYES &amp; J. L. WALSTON" box="[272,559,429,455]" journalOrPublisher="Myotis" pageId="13" pageNumber="218" pagination="35 - 122" part="39" refId="ref21801" refString="HENDRICHSEN, D. K., P. J. J. BATES, B. D. HAYES, and J. L. WALSTON. 2001. Recent records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Vietnam with six species new to the country. Myotis, 39: 35 - 122." title="Recent records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Vietnam with six species new to the country" type="journal article" year="2001">
Hendrichsen 
<emphasis box="[427,486,429,455]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="218">et al.</emphasis>
, 
<date box="[500,645,428,455]" pageId="13" pageNumber="218" value="2001" valueMax="2065">2001 and 65</date>
</bibRefCitation>
– 
<quantity box="[145,227,463,489]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.9" pageId="13" pageNumber="218" unit="mm" value="69.0">69 mm</quantity>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="BORISSENKO, A. V. &amp; S. V. KRUSKOP" bookContentInfo="211 pp." box="[265,633,463,489]" journalOrPublisher="Joint Russian - Vietnamese Science and Technological Tropical Centre and Zoological Museum of Moscow. M. V. Lomonosov State University, Moscow" pageId="13" pageNumber="218" refId="ref21281" refString="BORISSENKO, A. V., and S. V. KRUSKOP. 2003. Bats of Vietnam and adjacent territories: an identification manual. Joint Russian - Vietnamese Science and Technological Tropical Centre and Zoological Museum of Moscow. M. V. Lomonosov State University, Moscow, 211 pp." title="Bats of Vietnam and adjacent territories: an identification manual." type="book" year="2003">Borissenko and Kruskop, 2003</bibRefCitation>
). The dorsal pelage is dark grey-brown with the roots almost black. The ventral pelage is paler with grey hair tips and dark roots. The skull and teeth are robust. The second upper premolar (P3) is about half to two-thirds the crown area and height of the first (P2) and is slightly displaced internally. Likewise, the second lower premolar (P3) is half to two- thirds the crown area and height of the first (P2) and compressed in the toothrow.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="218" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[130,646,163,1529]" box="[130,309,864,890]" pageId="13" pageNumber="218">
<emphasis box="[130,309,864,890]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="218">Similar species</emphasis>
</paragraph>
